 mobilization, even when this takes place in a ‘domain of losses’ that exposes them to high levels of risk. It follows four women’s organizations who break with traditional gender norms and defy armed groups’ social and territorial control, exposing them to retributive punishment. It provides rich evidence to document how women are able to surmount the barriers to mobilization when they frame their actions in terms of resistance, rather than fear.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFeminismzColombia. 0aSocial movementszColombia. 0aWomenzColombiaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aFeminism, Colombia, grassroots women’s organizations, grassroot, social movement, gender justice, armed conflict, violence, violence against women, mobilize, resist, mother, carer, peacemaker, revolutionary, gendered, mobilization, resistance, Liga de Mujeres Desplazadas, Conflict Zone, Feminist Resistance, Afromupaz, Intersectional, Cuerpo y Cara de Mujer, La Soledad, Grassroots Mobilization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978827134?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978827134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978827134/original  a978-3-11-076647-9  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK